#1942
@@RReaver Toll Barricade@@N~
@@RSalvaged timber walls stretch between two packed-earth mounds here, blocking the road's southern approach to the caravan yards with a gate of lashed spear-shafts and seized wagon-sides.@@N @@yToll-marker posts flank the gate on both sides,@@N each hung with bronze disks engraved with the Yard Band's fee schedule: one disk per traveler, two per beast, four per full wagon. @@bDried blood darkens the packed earth in front of the gate,@@N evidence of negotiations that did not go well for one party. Armed reaver sentries stand at the gate and at both mound-tops, their positions giving clear sight-lines north up the approach corridor. Behind the gate, the caravan yard flats spread south toward the palm ring — close enough now to smell the oasis water on the wind. The barricade was not built to keep travelers out; it was built to ensure they cannot pass without paying.
~
