#1956
@@yWaystone Gnomon Base@@N~
@@yThe secondary observation position beyond the survey post ruins is dominated by the original gnomon-base stone that was removed from the main post and rolled here, apparently to clear space for the Water Court's construction work.@@N @@yThe stone is a natural limestone pillar,@@N uncut but remarkably regular, roughly a forearm's length across and twice that in height. Shadow marks ground into its north face show precisely where the noon shadow fell at winter and summer solstice, calibration lines the Keepers maintained for at least a century of measurements. The stone cannot be moved by any ordinary means — it was rolled here on hardwood rollers and the groove it left in the basin margin soil is still visible. The gnomon base is the oldest artifact in the oasis, predating the Keeper road network, predating the Ledger Kingdom — a natural landmark that attracted measurement before measurement had a name.
~
