0 -1 1955
E
gnomon stone~
The natural limestone pillar served as the calibration reference for every survey departure from the Great Oasis for at least two centuries. Its shadow marks are worn into the stone's north face at precise seasonal angles, and the measurement cipher carved into its base translates as the invariant point from which all distances are measured. The stone weighs more than a small house.
~
S
#1957
@@aCentral Basin Shore@@N~
@@aThe great basin opens here — a broad, still body of spring-fed water perhaps a hundred paces across,@@N its surface the deep, true blue of water that has never seen a drought's bottom. @@aDate palms ring the shore at the basin's edge, their roots drinking directly from the spring-water table,@@N their trunks carved with the allocation marks and history tallies of generations of Water Court administration. The Spring Wardens maintain a distribution platform on the north shore where the water-draw queue forms each morning. @@lA low current moves across the basin surface from a spring vent on the east shore,@@N marking the path of live water from the aquifer below. The basin is smaller than it was in the Water Court's prime — salt-bloom margins on the basin's south shore show where it has retreated from its historic high-water line — but it lives. This is the heart of everything the oasis was and is.
~
