0 -1 1962
E
basin water~
The water is cold, even in the height of summer — it comes directly from the deep aquifer, passing through limestone that maintains a constant temperature far below the desert surface. Drinking it without permission from the Water Clerk is technically a charter violation, though the Wardens enforce this selectively.
~
E
salt bloom~
The pale crust at the basin's southern margin is a salt bloom — mineral residue left behind as the water table dropped and the basin retreated from its historic high-water line. The bloom is not natural to this kind of water; it is the signature of aquifer stress, visible proof of the Ninth Meridian drought's legacy persisting in the soil.
~
S
#1958
@@yEast Shore Garden Margin@@N~
@@yThe eastern shore of the basin is cultivated more intensively than the other margins,@@N the soil here being the deepest and most water-enriched in the whole oasis. @@bSmall irrigated plots run from the shoreline back toward the palm ring,@@N each one growing a different herb or root vegetable, separated by low clay borders that direct the basin's edge-seepage to each row in turn. Reed Tender allocation markers identify each plot's cultivator, though the Reed Tender tradition now survives in only one practitioner. The caravan receiving yard was once visible from this shore; a gap in the palm ring to the east shows where the yard infrastructure was removed or dismantled. @@aThe basin reflects the palm canopy here in a near-perfect mirror that doubles the oasis's apparent size.@@N
~
