#1961
@@yHerb Terrace Footpath@@N~
@@yThe garden's lower terraces are given over to medicinal herbs whose cultivation requirements the Reed Tenders have refined over generations:@@N wormwood for fever, salt-sage for wound poultice, desert aloe in earthenware pots sunk to their rims in the loam. @@bThe footpath between terrace levels is worn smooth by the Tender's daily rounds,@@N the clay borders of each plot showing the careful shaping of someone who understands water management as a craft. Irrigation-channel covers made from flat stones can be moved to redirect flow between terraces — the system works without mechanical pumping or external water input beyond what the basin seepage provides. Small pottery markers at each plot's edge record the plant name, the cultivation date, and the medicinal application in the Reed Tender's hand. The path continues down to a lower access point in the palm ring.
