#1962
@@yWestern Waystone@@N~
@@yOne of the twelve original Keeper waystones still stands here at the basin's western edge,@@N a rectangular limestone slab nearly two body-lengths tall, its four faces inscribed with directional glyphs and distance marks pointing toward each of the recognized caravan routes. @@yThe western face, pointing toward the Eastern Desert road, is the best-preserved:@@N it records the heading, the distance to the first waypoint, and the water-draw entitlement for travelers arriving by the western route. A carved hand below the inscription points west with one finger — the Keeper way of indicating the primary direction this stone served. The charter inscription on the south face has been reinforced with red ochre at some point within living memory, suggesting someone cared enough about its survival to maintain it. The Western Waystone is the most frequently referenced inscription in the Spring Wardens' administrative records.
~
