#1963
@@yLower Garden Terrace@@N~
@@bThe lowest terrace of the Reed Tender's garden is the oldest, its stone retaining walls dating to the original Ledger Kingdom construction when the garden was first laid out as part of the Toll Pavilion's ornamental landscape program.@@N The wall-stones fit with a precision the reavers did not bring to their salvaged-timber constructions — each block shaped to interlock without mortar. @@aBasin seepage feeds this terrace continuously,@@N keeping the soil moist to a depth that the Tender's probing stick measures daily. Three ancient date palms occupy the terrace corners, their trunks too large for two people to embrace, their history carved in allocation-marks that go back to the Water Court period. A worn stone step at the terrace's south end gives access to a path toward the tool storage area within the palm ring.
