#1964
@@ySouthwestern Waystone@@N~
@@yThe Southwestern Waystone faces toward the old Twin Basin route — the road that once connected this oasis to the Southern Oasis through a chain of relay stations and signal towers that the Twin Basin Compact maintained.@@N @@bThe waystone's southwestern face is weathered more than the others,@@N catching the full force of the grit-laden southwest wind that blows most afternoons. Despite the weathering, the text recording the Twin Basin Compact's mutual-aid obligations is still legible: each oasis was required to maintain three days' emergency water supply for travelers from the other, and to provide safe conduct for compact messengers. @@yThe compact failed during the post-Ninth Meridian drought when both oases were struggling simultaneously,@@N but the stone's inscription does not record this — it records only the original agreement, in the optimistic voice of an administration that believed the compact would last as long as the road.
