#1965
@@yReed Tender's Tool Shed@@N~
@@bA low stone structure in the palm ring's interior houses the Last Reed Tender's cultivation equipment:@@N hand-trowels, channel-clearing rakes, seed-sorting boards, pottery measurement cups, and the specialized tools for pruning date palms at height. @@bThe shed's organization reflects decades of practice@@N — every tool has a designated hook or shelf, the most-used implements nearest the door, the specialist equipment stored in the back where it stays cool. A ledger volume on a stone shelf records the garden's full cultivation history in the Tender's precise hand: planting dates, yields, disease treatments, and annual notes on the basin's water level as it affects the terraces. The shed is locked from the outside with a wooden bar, but the lock is courtesy, not security — there is nothing here that any reaver would want to steal.
