#1971
@@yPavilion Approach@@N~
@@yThe south margin of the oasis opens here onto the approach road that leads to the Toll Pavilion ruins — and the boundary between Spring Warden territory and Wellmouth Creed occupation is immediately legible in the landscape.@@N @@pOn the Synod side of the transition, hanging bronze censers swing from ropes strung between the outer colonnade columns,@@N releasing smoke that drifts toward the oasis in deliberate liturgical pattern. @@pJackal sigils have been painted on every flat stone surface facing the oasis,@@N in the Wellmouth Creed's distinctive blue-and-copper palette. The road's surface changes here from maintained palm-loam to crushed ochre stone that the Synod has spread to mark its processional routes. The Warden warning-stone stands at the approach's western edge; an answering Synod inscription-stone stands on the eastern edge, reading in the Creed's liturgical script: here the mouth of the earth begins to speak. A gateway made of two broken colonnade columns flanking the road marks the boundary the reavers and the Synod have both agreed not to contest.
~
