#1972
@@yShattered Colonnade Entry@@N~
@@yThe grand entrance to the Toll Pavilion was once framed by a double colonnade of limestone columns that travelers walked between as a processional preparation for the Water Court's formal procedures.@@N Half of the columns have fallen, their drums scattered across the entry plaza, their carved bases still holding the foundations in place. @@pThe Wellmouth Creed has colonized what remains:@@N bronze censers hang from ropes strung between the standing column-tops, swinging in slow arcs and trailing the Synod's heavy incense through the air. @@pJackal-sigil banners in blue and copper hang from the surviving column shafts,@@N and the entry plaza's stone surface has been repainted with the Creed's well-mouth mandala — a circle of concentric rings representing the oasis spring seen from above. The colonnade still conveys grandeur through its ruins. The Wellmouth Creed chose this location for their occupation because that grandeur transfers to them, however unearned.
~
