@@yOuter Portico@@N~
@@pThe outer portico of the Toll Pavilion preserves more of its original roofing than any other section — three limestone slabs still span the colonnade here,@@N casting a deep rectangular shadow that Spring Acolytes have turned into a ritual station. @@pA carved stone basin originally used for hand-washing before Water Court proceedings now holds a dark liquid that the Creed uses for libation rites,@@N its original Keeper inscriptions painted over with the well-mouth formula. The portico walls are covered from floor to surviving-roof in Synod text: liturgical passages in the Creed's distinctive block-letter script, water-theology diagrams, and devotional graffiti added by individual initiates over years of occupation. The smell of incense is stronger here than at the entry, layered with something organic underneath — old ritual offering material that has been renewed too many times to fully clean away. Two Spring Acolytes maintain the libation basin as a permanent duty station.
