@@bThe pavilion's central nave was the main passage connecting the outer colonnade to the judicial dais,@@N a wide formal corridor that once saw Water Court processions, charter presentations, and the formal arrival of High Water Judges in their full administrative regalia. @@bAn earthquake — the same event that destroyed the original Measuring House a generation before the Toll Pavilion was built — has left a fault-line crack running the full width of the nave floor,@@N offset by two hand-spans at its widest point and requiring a careful step to cross safely. @@pThe Wellmouth Creed has painted the crack with silver wash and designated it a sacred boundary:@@N a painted text on the floor on either side reads one side is thirst, one side is water. The Creed's theology is not subtle. Basin Chanters can be heard in the depths of the pavilion, their rhythmic drone echoing off the surviving stone surfaces.
