0 -1 1977
E
altar~
The Wellmouth altar's liturgical instruments include a well-mouth mandala painted on cured hide using copper-derived blue and gold pigment, three silver bowls in graduated sizes for water offerings of different grades, and a jackal-head censer mounted on a stone stand that was once a water-court seal-press. The altar is rebuilt after each major ceremony, the Hierophant apparently finding the process of construction itself ritually significant.
~
E
dais chair base~
Four heavy iron brackets are still bolted into the dais floor where the High Water Judge's chair stood. The bracket design suggests a chair of considerable weight and permanence — not the portable folding seat of a traveling official, but a throne-equivalent that was intended to stay in place for generations. Someone has carved a well-mouth mandala into the bracket plate between the front two brackets, claiming the throne-space for the Creed.
~
S
#1977
@@yJudge's Outer Hall@@N~
@@yThe outer hall beside the judicial dais was where charter clerks maintained their administrative stations during proceedings — long stone tables built into the walls still hold the remains of the filing system that organized every water-right case that came before the High Water Court.@@N @@bMost of the documents were destroyed during the Battle of the Dry Basin@@N — the fighting came through this hall, and the fire damage on the south wall records where a torch-basket was overturned during the fighting. @@pThe Wellmouth Creed uses the clerk's tables as a library of sorts for their liturgical texts,@@N the carved stone surfaces now holding bound volumes of the Creed's scripture alongside the few surviving Water Court documents that the Synod considers theologically relevant. Two Spring Acolytes in the hall are copying text from an original charter fragment onto fresh hide using the Creed's calligraphic style — rewriting history into liturgy in real time.
~
