@@yCharter Registry Alcove@@N~
@@bThe charter registry was the most heavily-used administrative space in the Toll Pavilion — the room where caravan representatives submitted their water-draw applications and received their stamped allocations in exchange.@@N The registry's counter, a long limestone bar with iron-pin document holders along its face, is still intact, embedded in the wall and immovable. @@pThe Wellmouth Creed has converted the counter into a conversion station:@@N a Wellmouth Priest stands at the counter during official hours and issues the Creed's own water-authorization tokens to travelers who complete the Creed's ritual procedure. The tokens are meaningless outside the Synod's territorial claim, but within the pavilion, refusing one is equivalent to refusing the Hierophant's authority. A stack of the tokens — small clay disks stamped with the well-mouth mandala — sits beside the priest's place on the counter. The irony of replacing Water Court bureaucracy with cult bureaucracy has not been lost on the Spring Wardens.
