#1980
@@pBasin Chanting Hall@@N~
@@pThe largest enclosed space in the Toll Pavilion was originally a waiting hall where caravans queued for charter review — its acoustic properties, a product of its barrel-vaulted ceiling and fitted stone walls, were incidental to its administrative function.@@N The Wellmouth Creed discovered those acoustics immediately and converted the hall to its primary ritual use: the continuous liturgical chant that the Basin Chanters maintain in rotating shifts around the clock. @@pThe sound fills the hall from floor to vault — a rhythmic, multi-voiced drone that carries the Creed's water-theology in repetitive cycles,@@N each cycle ending with the phrase the mouth speaks water in the Keeper's old administrative script. The chanters sit in formal rows facing the hall's south end, where a painted well-mouth mandala covers the full wall. @@pThe chanting does not stop when strangers enter.@@N It does not react to anything that happens in the hall — the Chanters have been trained to maintain the liturgy through any interruption short of violence.
~
