#1981
@@pProcessional Descent@@N~
@@pThe stairway descending from the chanting hall into the pavilion's lower ritual spaces was originally a service corridor used by cistern workers — a functional passage whose stone walls were undecorated and whose width accommodated the equipment of hydraulic maintenance work.@@N The Wellmouth Creed has transformed it into a devotional descent: every step-face has been painted with a line of liturgical text, so that walking down becomes a reading exercise in the Creed's water-theology. @@pCenser brackets on the walls fill the descent with incense smoke,@@N thickening as one goes deeper, creating a sensory transition from the chanting hall above to the ritual chambers below. The passage smells of hot metal, resin smoke, and something underneath that might be the stone's natural mineral character or might be the smell of water held in the cistern infrastructure below. The chanting from above echoes down the stairway in fragmented phrases.
