#1982
@@pRitual Cistern Crossing@@N~
@@pThe passage here crosses above one of the cistern ring's buried channels,@@N and the Wellmouth Creed has made this fact central to the space's ritual identity: a glass panel set into the floor reveals the channel below, @@lthe water moving slowly through the limestone-cut channel in a cold, dark current that the Creed teaches is the literal voice of the sleeping earth deity.@@N @@pPainted text around the glass panel's frame records the Creed's theology of spring-speak:@@N the water's movement is the deity's breath, the mineral tang is its voice, and the spring itself is the deity's mouth through which it speaks to the surface world. The panel is thick enough to walk on safely, though the Wellmouth Priests instruct initiates to walk around it in a specific direction as part of the crossing rite. The cistern sound — a faint, rhythmic burble audible through the floor — is real, not manufactured.
