0 -1 1985
E
salt circles~
Five concentric salt circles of different diameters cover the chamber floor. The largest is two paces across; the smallest barely fits a kneeling person. The circles are renewed after each initiation ceremony from a store of imported salt kept in sealed jars at the chamber's perimeter — the Creed sources the salt from a specific coastal supplier whose product they consider ritually pure. A sixth circle, not yet drawn, is implied by the spacing of the first five.
~
E
ritual basins~
The four corner basins are labeled in the Creed's liturgical script with the water's source and spiritual grade: first-order spring (direct surface contact), second-order cistern (north chamber overflow), third-order aquifer (deep channel draw), and fourth-order reclaimed (condensation from deep stone). The theology assigns higher spiritual potency to deeper water. The fourth-order basin holds only a few drops, condensation being difficult to collect in useful quantity.
~
S
#1985
@@pBlood Offering Passage@@N~
@@pThe passage between the salt oath chamber and the libation spaces is the most disturbing section of the pavilion for visitors unfamiliar with the Creed's practices:@@N the stone floor carries visible staining from offering material that has accumulated over years of ritual use, the drainage channel cut into the floor's center unable to fully clear the volume the Creed produces. @@pWallmounted brackets hold iron offering-hooks from which various ritual materials hang in labeled bundles,@@N each bundle's label recording the offering grade, the source date, and the liturgical purpose. The smell is organic and metallic in alternating layers that shift as one moves through the passage. @@pWellmouth Priests pass through here with the practiced indifference of people who have been doing the same work in the same space long enough to stop perceiving it.@@N The passage is not secret or hidden — the Creed wants visitors to see it, as evidence of the scale of their devotional commitment.
~
