#1991
@@pWellmouth Hierophant's Sanctum@@N~
@@pThe Hierophant's private sanctum is the visual opposite of the pavilion's public ritual spaces — where the public rooms are layered with symbol and decoration, the sanctum is nearly bare, its focus concentrated on a single object at the room's center.@@N @@lA natural limestone formation in the floor — the tip of a cistern chamber's vault, exposed by the Battle of the Dry Basin's structural damage — rises from the stone and has been identified by the Hierophant as the earth deity's literal mouth.@@N @@pWater seeps from a crack in the formation's peak with metronomic regularity, collecting in a polished basin that the Hierophant keeps immaculately clean.@@N Spring-water interpretation charts cover the walls — diagrams correlating seep-rate, mineral color, and temperature with theological predictions about the deity's spiritual state and intent. @@pThe Hierophant lives here, sleeps here, and spends most of every day in contact with the seeping stone,@@N listening for what the Creed's theology promises the earth deity is saying. The sanctum is the most sincere room in the pavilion — this is where the Wellmouth Creed's founder actually believes.
~
