1 1979 1990
E
limestone formation~
The limestone formation is a genuine geological feature — the exposed apex of a cistern vault that was cracked during the Battle of the Dry Basin and pushed upward by subsequent settling. The seep at its peak comes from water percolating through the cracked vault from the north cistern's overflow. The seep-rate varies with basin water levels, creating the fluctuation that the Hierophant interprets as the deity's speech. The Hierophant's interpretation charts correlate seep-rate with weather, season, and prayer content, finding patterns that may or may not exist in the data.
~
S
#1992
@@lNorth Cistern Descent@@N~
@@lThe stone stairway descending from the North Cistern Wellhead is the oldest engineering work still in active use at the oasis:@@N the Keeper survey crews cut these steps into the limestone bedrock during the first decade of the road network's construction, and every cistern worker since has used the same hand-worn edges and the same knee-bruising drop at the seventh step where the bedrock shifted. @@lFitted limestone walls carry the full history of cistern maintenance in their inscriptions:@@N water-level gauges calibrated to the basin surface above, flow-rate marks made by three generations of sluice masters, and the formal engineering text of the Cistern Charter recording the North Cistern's purpose, capacity, and regulation mandate. @@aThe sound of water changes as one descends@@N — the surface world's wind and bird-sound falls away and is replaced by the cistern ring's constant low conversation of water and stone.
~
