0 -1 2000
E
sluice console~
The sixteen-lever sluice console is the operational heart of the cistern ring. Each lever is labeled with its target gate's designation (North Primary, South Secondary, etc.) and calibration marks indicate the operational positions for each flow scenario. The four functional levers are worn smooth from regular use; the twelve non-functional levers are locked in their last-set positions by corrosion, preserving the settings that whoever last operated them chose before the system fell into partial disuse.
~
E
engineering inscriptions~
The wall documentation covers the complete design specification of the cistern ring: chamber volumes, flow rates, sluice gate dimensions, maintenance schedules, and emergency procedures. The emergency procedures section, covering six walls, details responses to drought, flood, earthquake, siege, and what the Keepers called civil disruption — a category that the Battle of the Dry Basin apparently qualified as, given the damage. The margin of the civil disruption section carries a handwritten note: this procedure was not sufficient.
~
S
#1997
@@lEast Mechanism Alcove@@N~
@@lThe east alcove off the sluice control chamber houses the secondary control equipment for the East Cistern's sluice system — the specialized valves and pressure gauges that monitored the deepest and most critical chamber in the ring.@@N @@lBronze pressure gauges still mounted on the alcove's east wall are the Keepers' most sophisticated surviving instruments:@@N graduated dial-faces with calibrated needles that respond to pressure changes in the cistern below, their mechanisms running on the same water pressure that powers the sluice system. Two of the four gauges still function. @@bThe working gauges show that pressure in the East Cistern chamber is higher than the operational norm,@@N a reading consistent with the flooded condition of the east section — the water is not flowing through the circuit the way the Keepers designed it to. The alcove smells strongly of the mineral-rich deep water.
~
