#2014
@@lSubterranean Channel Fork@@N~
@@lThe main flooded passage forks here,@@N its original engineering purpose — splitting flow between the East Cistern's primary chamber and an overflow collection gallery — now serving as a junction between the main submerged route south and an archive side-chamber to the east. @@lThe fork's structural elements are the most elaborate in the flooded zone:@@N four stone piers support the ceiling at the junction, each carved with flow-direction markers that once guided maintenance workers through a space that would have been familiar territory to them. The current is faint but detectable here, moving consistently southward — evidence that the aquifer below the East Cistern still has active pressure, still moving water through the system at whatever rate the cracked limestone allows. Something about the fork's proportions feels like it was designed for larger occupants than the Keeper survey crews.
~
