@@lThe approach passage south of the alcove narrows and descends sharply,@@N the aquifer channel cutting deeper into the natural limestone as it approaches the Wyrm's primary lair zone. @@lThe walls here carry the densest concentration of physical evidence of the creature's presence:@@N mineral scrape marks overlap in layers, the oldest worn nearly smooth and the newest still showing the raw limestone beneath the removed deposit. The scale impressions in the passage floor are so numerous they cover every square arm-length of the sediment. The current is negligible here — the water is nearly still, suggesting the Wyrm's lair acts as a pressure sink that reduces the hydraulic gradient in the surrounding passages. @@lThe temperature drops another degree in this approach.@@N Something very large is close, and its presence has modified the local environment in ways the geology alone does not explain.
~
